LII.y Of thunderbolts themselves several varieties are reported. Those that come with a dry flash do not cause a fire but an explosion. The smoky ones do not burn but blac-ken. There is a third sort, called ⁴ bright thunderboltS,’ of an extremely remark- able nature3 this kind drains casks dry without damaging their lids and without leaving any other trace, and melts gold and copper and silver in their bags without singeing the bags themselves at all, and even without melting the wax seal. Marcia, a lady of high station at Rome, was struck by lightning when enceinte, and though the child was killed, she herself survive-d without being otherwise injured. Among the portents in connexion with Catiline, a town—councillor of Pompei named Marcus Herennius was struck by lightning on a fine day.
